osgi.core and I've not run any tests per instructions. I'll include a note about what I've added and the test coverage analysis.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Reassessing TestBundle implementation**\\n\\nI'm reconsidering whether the TestBundle implementation is too broad, as it seems to retest the Bundle API. The assertions like bundle.getBundleId, getSymbolicName, and getState could just end up duplicating tests for osgi.core Bundle. I wonder if asserting that getBundle is the same would suffice without needing those additional assertions. While those extra checks might show the bundle's usability, they don't seem essential for testing non-null bundle association. Perhaps I could streamline by focusing mainly on getSymbolicName in TestBundle and simplifying the methods that throw exceptions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering minimal implementation**\\n\\nI’m thinking of keeping things minimal. Actually, TestBundle implements the library's public API, which is good. But would a reviewer raise concerns about using a private SimpleLogEntry that isn’t part of the public API? Existing tests seem to handle it fine since the library has no implementation. I could also consider a simpler test for LogListener that extends EventListener to avoid unnecessary helpers, but that might be too trivial. The bundle getter is a public feature, and the existing test only checks for null. There’s no need for any direct reflection or serialization.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Implemented a new test in:\n\n`tests/src/org.osgi/org.osgi.service.log/1.3.0/src/test/java/org_osgi/org_osgi_service_log/Org_osgi_service_logTest.java`\n\nCurrent coverage in the file already included:\n- `LogService` severity constants.\n- All `LogService.log(...)` overloads.\n- Custom integer log levels and nullable messages/exceptions.\n- `ServiceReference` association on log entries.\n- `LogReaderService` listener registration/removal behavior.\n- Duplicate listener registration by identity.\n- `getLog()` ordering and snapshot behavior.\n\nNew uncovered feature added:\n- `LogEntry#getBundle()` with a non-null originating `Bundle`, delivered through a `LogListener`.\n\nChanges made:\n- Added `logEntryCanExposeOriginatingBundleToListener()`.\n- Added a small `TestBundle` implementation to model an originating OSGi bundle using public OSGi APIs only.\n- Added an accessor to `RecordingLogListener` so the new test can inspect the delivered `LogEntry`.\n\nTests were not run, per instruction.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_063c30b310b518c10169f7b5179a1c8191b6ba25b1c6473954\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 388, "output": 1127, "cacheRead": 29184, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30699, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "stop", "timestamp": 1777841417652, "responseId": "resp_063c30b310b518c10169f7b50a16d8819188c8b51aec177cea"}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating project modifications**\n\nI notice the project has a .log file that's ignored, and I think it might affect tests. I need to modify this situation while keeping in mind that the user expects changes. The worktree might not be tracking properly, which could account for the filename issue. There's a different concern regarding using only the provided library versions. I should clarify that \"LogEntry.getBundle\" methods come from osgi.core and I've not run any tests per instructions. I'll include a note about what I've added and the test coverage analysis.\n\n**Reassessing TestBundle implementation**\n\nI'm reconsidering whether the TestBundle implementation is too broad, as it seems to retest the Bundle API. The assertions like bundle.getBundleId, getSymbolicName, and getState could just end up duplicating tests for osgi.core Bundle. I wonder if asserting that getBundle is the same would suffice without needing those additional assertions. While those extra checks might show the bundle's usability, they don't seem essential for testing non-null bundle association. Perhaps I could streamline by focusing mainly on getSymbolicName in TestBundle and simplifying the methods that throw exceptions.\n\n**Considering minimal implementation**\n\nI’m thinking of keeping things minimal. Actually, TestBundle implements the library's public API, which is good. But would a reviewer raise concerns about using a private SimpleLogEntry that isn’t part of the public API? Existing tests seem to handle it fine since the library has no implementation. I could also consider a simpler test for LogListener that extends EventListener to avoid unnecessary helpers, but that might be too trivial. The bundle getter is a public feature, and the existing test only checks for null. There’s no need for any direct reflection or serialization.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_063c